  footnotes: []
english:
  title: 'In Praise of Two Ink Bamboo Paintings: A Response to Master Mongyeo of Songgwangsa'
  author: Lee Gyeong-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On Bamboo Shoots in Snow

    Bamboo endures the cold—this is its nature.
    Yet I have never heard of shoots breaking through snow.
    Once, a filial son's devotion moved heaven and earth;
    his tears brought forth winter bamboo,
    offered to a mother's delight.

    But you are no mere dharma-body,
    no transformation bound to seasons.
    Your luminous form shines clear and unchanged—
    unaffected by time's turning wheel.
    The dharma's solemn truth mirrors your form;
    why then should you know hot and cold?

    On Two Wind-Tossed Bamboo Groves

    In the great wind's path, all things are struck alike.
    Why then does one grove dance while the other stands still?

    One cluster, battered by the gale,
    shakes ceaselessly without rest.
    One stands firm and upright,
    rooted in its own quietude.

    Thus two travelers walk the path of Zen together:
    one has awakened to sudden insight,
    the mind already ripened and burning bright.
    The other still wanders in confusion,
    thoughts arising in endless streams.

    When the wandering mind returns
    and listens to the nature of listening itself,
    then shaking and stillness both dissolve away.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The filial son is likely Dong Yong or another figure from Chinese tradition whose tears of devotion caused bamboo shoots to miraculously appear in winter.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'dharma-body' and references to dharma suggest this is written for a Buddhist monk or as a meditation on Buddhist philosophy.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem uses two bamboo groves as a metaphor for different stages of spiritual development in Zen Buddhism.
